BT /F2 18 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 748 Tm (Symplichain Hackathon Submission) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 715 Tm (This repository contains my submission for the Symplichain Software Engineering Intern) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 700 Tm (hackathon.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 677 Tm (- Written response: `submission.pdf`) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 662 Tm (- CI/CD workflow: `.github/workflows/deploy.yml`) Tj ET
BT /F2 14 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 639 Tm (Part 1: Shared Gateway Problem) Tj ET
BT /F2 12 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 611 Tm (Architecture) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 586 Tm (I would keep the design simple:) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 563 Tm (- `API gateway \(Django/FastAPI\)`: receives requests from all customers) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 548 Tm (- `Redis`: stores per-customer queues and scheduler state) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 533 Tm (- `Celery`: runs the dispatcher and retry jobs) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 518 Tm (- `PostgreSQL`: stores request status and audit trail) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 503 Tm (- `External API`: limited to 3 requests/second) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 480 Tm (Why this approach:) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 457 Tm (- The main challenge is not computation, it is outbound traffic control) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 442 Tm (- Redis + Celery is enough for this scale and much cheaper than introducing Kafka) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 427 Tm (- Keeping the rate limiter in one place makes the system easier to reason about) Tj ET
BT /F2 12 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 404 Tm (How I Would Enforce the 3 req/sec Limit) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 379 Tm (I would not allow every worker to call the external API directly.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 356 Tm (- Each customer gets a Redis queue: `queue:<customer_id>`) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 341 Tm (- The gateway validates the request quickly, stores its metadata, and pushes it to that) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 84 326 Tm (queue) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 311 Tm (- A single dispatcher runs once every second) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 296 Tm (- On each tick, it selects at most 3 requests total and sends them to the external API) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 273 Tm (Why this guarantees the limit:) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 250 Tm (- Only the dispatcher is allowed to make outbound calls) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 235 Tm (- The dispatcher has a hard cap of 3 sends per second) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 220 Tm (- Any excess traffic simply waits in Redis) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 197 Tm (If I wanted high availability later, I would run a standby dispatcher and protect the active) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 182 Tm (one with a Redis lock.) Tj ET
BT /F2 12 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 159 Tm (Fairness Across Customers) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 134 Tm (A single global FIFO queue is simple, but not fair. One heavy customer could fill the queue) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 119 Tm (and delay everyone else.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 96 Tm (To avoid that, I would use **per-customer queues with round-robin scheduling**:) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 73 Tm (- Maintain one queue per customer) Tj ET
endstream
endobj
4 0 obj
<< /Length 3088 >>
stream
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 748 Tm (- Keep a rotating pointer to the next customer to serve) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 733 Tm (- In each 1-second cycle, take at most 1 request from a customer before moving to the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 84 718 Tm (next one) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 703 Tm (- Continue until 3 requests are selected) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 680 Tm (This avoids starvation. A noisy customer can still use spare capacity, but not at the cost) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 665 Tm (of blocking everyone else.) Tj ET
BT /F2 12 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 642 Tm (Retry Strategy) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 617 Tm (Retries should be selective:) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 594 Tm (- `Retryable`: timeout, temporary 5xx, connection reset, occasional 429) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 579 Tm (- `Non-retryable`: invalid payload, auth failure, bad request) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 556 Tm (Policy:) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 533 Tm (- Exponential backoff with jitter) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 518 Tm (- Example delays: 2s, 5s, 15s, 30s, 60s) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 503 Tm (- Max 5 attempts) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 488 Tm (- After that, mark the request as `failed` and surface it for review) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 465 Tm (Why:) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 442 Tm (- Backoff prevents hammering a slow dependency) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 427 Tm (- Jitter avoids synchronized retries) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 412 Tm (- Not retrying 4xx errors keeps the queue healthy) Tj ET
BT /F2 12 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 389 Tm (Request Flow) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 364 Tm (1. Customer sends request to the shared gateway.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 349 Tm (2. Gateway authenticates, validates, stores request metadata, and pushes the job into) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 90 334 Tm (that customer's Redis queue.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 319 Tm (3. Dispatcher wakes up every second.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 304 Tm (4. Dispatcher selects up to 3 jobs using round-robin across non-empty queues.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 289 Tm (5. Dispatcher sends requests to the external API.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 274 Tm (6. Success updates the request state.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 259 Tm (7. Retryable failures are rescheduled with backoff.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 244 Tm (8. Permanent failures are marked as failed.) Tj ET
BT /F2 12 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 221 Tm (Trade-offs) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 196 Tm (- `Why this approach:` simple, cheap, and easy to defend in production) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 181 Tm (- `Why not a global queue:` easier, but unfair during tenant bursts) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 166 Tm (- `Why not Kafka:` useful at larger scale, but too heavy for this problem) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 72 151 Tm (- `Why not worker-side throttling:` harder to guarantee a strict global limit across) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 1 0 0 1 84 136 Tm (multiple workers) Tj ET
BT /F2 14 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 113 Tm (Part 2: Mobile App Architecture) Tj ET
BT /F2 12 Tf 1 0 0 1 54 85 Tm (Interaction Model) Tj ET
endstream
endobj
